1c

scaling <- function(x) (x - mean(x, na.rm = TRUE)) / sd(x, na.rm = TRUE)

clust.scaled <- USArrests %>%
    map_df(scaling) %>%
    dist(method = 'euclidean') %>%
    hclust(method = 'complete')

clust.scaled$labels <- row.names(USArrests)[clust.scaled$order]
hclust.scale <- scale(USArrests)
hclust.scale_ <- hclust(dist(hclust.scale),method='complete')
plot(hclust.scale_)

plot(clust.scaled, lwd = 3, lty = 1, sub = "", hang = -1, axes = FALSE, xlab = '')
axis(side = 2, at = seq(0, 6, length.out = 3), lwd = 2)
mtext(seq(0, 6, length.out = 3), side = 2, at = seq(0, 6, length.out = 3), line = 1, las = 2)

2.3 Two largest loadings of pc1 is ozone and temp. As seen in the first question ozone and temp has high correlation. Ozone and temp has the most affect on pc1.

2.4

summary(pr.out_)$importance
##                             PC1       PC2       PC3       PC4
## Standard deviation     1.536294 0.9458106 0.6897738 0.5190919
## Proportion of Variance 0.590050 0.2236400 0.1189500 0.0673600
## Cumulative Proportion  0.590050 0.8136900 0.9326400 1.0000000

As seen from the cumulative proportion pc1 explains only 59 percent variance. the cumulative proportion for pc1 and pc2 is 81 percent. To explain 90 percent of total variance, we have to use cumulative proportion upto pc3.

biplot(pr.out_)

Ozone and temp has high correlation. In the biplot the xaxis is pc1 and y axis is pc2. The loadings of pc2 and pc1 are on right axis and top axis. The bottom left is bad radiation and wind and bad ozone and temp. Bottom right is bad radiation and wind and good temp and ozone. top left is bad ozone and temp and good radiation and wind. top right is good wind and radiation and good temp and ozone.
